[[File:Indian cultural zone.svg|thumb|300x300px|[[Greater India]] is a reflection of the historical Hindu realm.]] Hindu empires rose to power following the birth of Hinduism in the [[Indian subcontinent]]. Considered to be the greatest empire of its time in the world, the [[Maurya Empire]] under [[Chandragupta Maurya|Chandragupta]] and [[Ashoka]] became larger than British India, diplomatically engaging with [[Greece]], [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedonia]], [[Epirus (ancient state)|Epirus]], [[Cyrenaica|Cyrene]] and [[Egypt]].<ref>Sarkar, Benoy Kumar. “Hindu Political Philosophy.” ''Political Science Quarterly'', vol. 33, no. 4, 1918, pp. 485. ''JSTOR'', JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/2141603.</ref> The historical and geographic extent of Indian civilization is referred to as [[Greater India]] and encompasses empires that also practiced Dharmic faiths such as [[Buddhism]] and [[Jainism]].
The following list enumerates Hindu empires and dynasties in chronological order.
