{{BLP sources|date=May 2011}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Sharman Apt Russell | image = | imagesize = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = Sharman Apt | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1954}} | birth_place = [[Edwards Air Force Base]], [[California]], United States | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = [[novelist]], [[essay]]ist | nationality = American | period = 1980s to present | genre = | subject = | movement = | influences = | influenced = | signature = | website = {{URL|http://www.sharmanaptrussell.com/}} | spouse = | relatives = [[Milburn G. Apt]] (father) }} '''Sharman Apt Russell''' (born 1954) is a nature and science writer based in [[New Mexico]], United States. Her topics include citizen science, living in place, public lands grazing, [[archaeology]], flowers, butterflies, hunger, and [[Pantheism]].
==Biography== Russell was born at [[Edwards Air Force Base]] in the [[Mojave Desert]] in 1954, was raised in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], and settled in southern New Mexico in 1981. Russell is the daughter of test pilot [[Milburn G. Apt]], who was killed testing the [[Bell X-2]] in 1956.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Russell|first=Sharman Apt|title=Letter to My Father Concerning the State of the World|url=http://www.terrain.org/essays/23/russell.htm|journal=[[Terrain.org]]|issue=23|date=Winter–Spring 2009|issn=1932-9474|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref>
Russell is a professor emeritus in the Humanities Department at [[Western New Mexico University]] in [[Silver City, New Mexico|Silver City]], where she teaches writing for graduate students.<ref name="WNMU">{{cite web|url=http://www.wnmu.edu/academic/hum/russels2.shtml|title=Sharman Apt Russell|work=wnmu.edu|publisher=Western New Mexico University|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yzmzHIYh?url=http://www.wnmu.edu/academic/hum/russels2.shtml|archivedate=27 May 2011|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Russell received her MFA in Creative Writing from the [[University of Montana]] and her B.S. in Conservation and Natural Resources from the [[University of California, Berkeley]].
==Works== Russell's essays and short stories have been widely published and anthologized. Her collections of essays ''Songs of the Fluteplayer: Seasons of Life in the Southwest'' (Addison-Wesley, 1991; reprinted by University of Nebraska Press, 2000) won the 1992 [[Mountains and Plains Booksellers Award]] and [[New Mexico Zia Award]] and recounts her years as a back-to-the-lander in rural New Mexico. ''Standing in the Light: My Life as a Pantheist'' was a [[New Mexico Book Award]] finalist and one of Booklist's top ten religious books of 2008. Her book ''Diary of a Citizen Scientist: Chasing Tiger Beetles and Other New Ways of Engaging the World'' (Oregon State University Press, 2014) won the 2016 John Burroughs Medal for Distinguished Nature Writing,<ref>http://www.scsun-news.com/story/news/2016/03/14/silver-city-author-receive-john-burroughs-medal/81760198/</ref> the WILLA Award for Creative Nonfiction,<ref>http://www.womenwritingthewest.org/willaCurrentFinalists.html</ref> a New Mexico/Arizona Finalist Award,<ref>http://nmbookcoop.com/BookAwards/2015-finalists/2015-finalists.html</ref> and was listed by ''The Guardian'' as one of ten top nature books in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/grrlscientist/2014/dec/16/the-best-nature-books-of-2014 |title=The best nature books of 2014 |author=GrrlScientist |work=The Guardian |accessdate=May 15, 2016}}</ref> Her historical fantasy ''Teresa of the New World'' (Yucca Publishing) for ages 12 and up was released in March, 2015<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Teresa-New-World-Sharman-Russell/dp/1631580426 |title=Amazon.com: Teresa of the New World (9781631580420): Sharman Apt Russell: Books |accessdate=May 15, 2016}}</ref> and won the Arizona Authors Award for Fiction.<ref>http://www.azauthors.com/contest_winners.html</ref> Her eco-science-fiction Knocking on Heaven's Door (Yucca Publishing) came out in 2016 and won the New Mexico/Arizona Book Award for Science Fiction and the Arizona Author's Award for Fiction.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Knocking-Heavens-Door-Sharman-Russell-ebook/dp/B019WQU83Q?ie=UTF8&btkr=1&ref_=dp-kindle-redirect</ref>
''Hunger: An Unnatural History'' (Basic Books, 2005)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PFlAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PiAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6429,1760450&dq=sharman-apt-russell&hl=en|title=Feast For Hungry Readers|last=Scmid|first=Randolph E.|date=8 January 2006|work=Wilmington Star-News|page=4D|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref> was the result of a Rockefeller Fellowship at [[Bellagio (Italian region)|Bellagio]], [[Italy]], and ''An Obsession with Butterflies: Our Long Love Affair with a Singular Insect'' (Perseus Books, 2003) was a pick of independent booksellers in the Summer 2003 Book Sense 76. ''Anatomy of a Rose: Exploring the Secret Life of Flowers'' has been translated into [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[German language|German]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], with other books also translated into [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Italian language|Italian]]. Other awards for Russell are a [[Pushcart Prize]], the [[Henry Joseph Jackson Award]], and the [[Writers at Work Award]]. ''The Last Matriarch'' (University of New Mexico Press, 2000) is a novel about Paleolithic life in New Mexico some 11,000 years ago. ''The Humpbacked Fluteplayer'' (Knopf Books for Young Readers, 1994) is a fantasy for ages 8–12.
